#compdef bbin
# Documentation: source-direct extraction from upstream
# babashka/bbin src/babashka/bbin/cli.clj
# (**Clojure language**; uses **`babashka.cli`** — a
# small declarative CLI library that ships with the
# Babashka Clojure interpreter and dispatches by
# `:cmds` vectors.  Corpus's **first documented
# Clojure CLI library**.  Pivots from R301 _adorn
# (Nim cligen) into the Clojure ecosystem):
#   src/babashka/bbin/cli.clj line 6
#     (`[babashka.cli :as cli]` — Clojure REQUIRE
#     form; `:as cli` aliases the namespace to the
#     local symbol `cli`.  Clojure's `:require`
#     vectors are namespace-import directives in
#     the `(ns ...)` block)
#   src/babashka/bbin/cli.clj line 80
#     (`(cli/dispatch (full-commands run-opts')
#                     main-args {})` — babashka.cli's
#     PRIMARY ENTRY POINT.  `dispatch` takes a SEQ
#     of command maps + the argv + an opts map.  It
#     walks the command list, prefix-matches the
#     argv against `:cmds` vectors, then calls
#     `:fn` with the parsed-opts map)
#   src/babashka/bbin/cli.clj lines 24-58
#     (the COMMAND VECTOR — each map has shape:
#       `{:cmds VEC :fn FN :args->opts VEC :aliases MAP}`
#     where:
#       `:cmds`        ← the SUBCOMMAND PATH as a
#                        VECTOR of strings; empty
#                        vector `[]` is the DEFAULT
#                        when no subcommand given;
#                        multi-element vectors like
#                        `["migrate" "auto"]` are
#                        NESTED SUBCOMMANDS matched
#                        left-to-right
#       `:fn`          ← the HANDLER (a Clojure
#                        function-of-one-arg called
#                        with the parsed-opts map)
#       `:args->opts`  ← POSITIONAL-TO-OPTION MAP;
#                        e.g. `[:script/lib]` says
#                        "the first positional arg
#                        is bound to the option
#                        `:script/lib` in the parsed
#                        opts map".  Distinct from
#                        cli/install's flag-style
#                        opts because positionals
#                        are NOT prefixed with `--`
#       `:aliases`     ← SHORT-FLAG → LONG-OPT MAP
#                        (e.g. `{:T :tool}` makes
#                        `-T` an alias for `--tool`)
#   src/babashka/bbin/cli.clj lines 18-22
#     (`add-global-aliases` injects `{:h :help}` into
#     every command's `:aliases` map — so `-h` is
#     globally aliased to `--help`.  Corpus's
#     **first documented post-spec-decoration
#     pattern**: aliases are computed by mapping
#     `assoc-in [:aliases :h] :help` over the
#     command list, rather than declared in each
#     command spec.  Functional composition over
#     spec mutation)
# Reference accessed: 2026-05-31 via gh api.
#
# README option enumeration (src/babashka/bbin/
# README.md sections "Supported Options" + "CLI"):
#   install [script]    --as
#                       --git/sha
#                       --git/tag
#                       --git/url
#                       --latest-sha
#                       --local/root
#                       --main-opts
#                       --mvn/version
#                       --ns-default
#                       --tool / -T
#   uninstall [script]  (no documented options)
#   ls                  (no documented options)
#   bin                 (no documented options)
#   version             (no documented options)
#   help                (no documented options)
#   migrate             (no documented options)
#   migrate auto        (no documented options)
#   upgrade [script]    (gated on util/upgrade-
#                       enabled?  — present in cli.
#                       clj as `(when (util/upgrade-
#                       enabled?) ...)`)
#
# bbin is **the** standard Babashka script installer
# — installs any Babashka script or project with one
# command, from a Maven coord, Git URL, raw URL, or
# local path.  Authored by rads (Rad Cooper) under
# the babashka GitHub org.  Hardcoded entry point:
# `(when (= *file* (System/getProperty "babashka.
# file")) (apply -main *command-line-args*))` —
# Babashka's MAIN-FILE GUARD pattern (corpus's
# **first documented Babashka `*file*` guard
# pattern**).  Sister tools: bb (Babashka itself,
# already in corpus as `_bb`), neil (Clojure project
# tool, already in corpus as `_neil`).
#
# Critical extraction note: bbin uses **`babashka.
# cli` declarative dispatch** at cli.clj:80 —
# babashka.cli's `dispatch` function is a
# DECLARATIVE PREFIX-DISPATCHER: takes a VECTOR of
# command maps, prefix-matches the argv against
# `:cmds` vectors, then routes to the `:fn` for the
# matching command.  Distinct from R301 Nim cligen
# (proc-signature-as-spec compile-time macro),
# R296 Julia Comonicon (function-signature-as-spec
# compile-time macro), R295 CL clingon (CLOS
# subclassing for subcommands), R290 Racket
# `command-line` (s-expression DSL macro), and R287
# Nim parseopt (manual `for kind, key, val in
# getopt():` loop).  babashka.cli's approach: a
# PLAIN CLOJURE DATA STRUCTURE (vector of maps) IS
# THE COMMAND SPEC.  No macros, no records, no DSL.
# Pure data.  Documents the **plain-data-as-CLI-spec
# pattern** — sister to (but distinct from) R295 CL
# clingon's `make-command` constructor (which
# returns a CLOS instance, not raw plist).  Closest
# analog: Go cobra's `&cobra.Command{...}` struct
# literal — but Clojure goes further because the
# vector of command maps can be COMPUTED at runtime
# by ordinary `(map ...)` / `(filter ...)` /
# `(remove nil?)` calls (see line 60 `remove nil?`
# for the conditional `upgrade` command).  Corpus's
# **first documented compute-the-spec-with-data-
# functions CLI pattern**.  Extends cross-language
# CLI taxonomy to FORTY-ONE library variants:
# Rust (6), Go (4), Python (3), Crystal 1 (R269),
# Haskell (R270), OCaml (R271), C (R272),
# Java (R276), Kotlin (R277), Scala (R278),
# Dart (R279), Ruby (R280), Perl (R281),
# PHP (R282), Swift (R283), F# (R284), Lua (R285),
# C# (R286), Nim 1 parseopt (R287), Zig (R288),
# D (R289), Racket (R290), Common Lisp 1 (R291),
# Erlang (R292), Tcl (R293), Pharo Smalltalk (R294),
# Common Lisp 2 clingon (R295), Julia (R296),
# SWI-Prolog optparse (R297), Pony stdlib cli (R298),
# Crystal 2 Admiral (R299), V stdlib `flag` (R300),
# Nim 2 cligen (R301), **Clojure babashka.cli**
# (R302 — NEW).  **MAJOR PATTERN MILESTONE**: 41
# cross-language CLI library variants documented.
#
# Critical extraction note: bbin uses **nested
# subcommand vectors** at cli.clj:35 — `:cmds
# ["migrate" "auto"]` is a TWO-ELEMENT subcommand
# path: `bbin migrate auto` matches this command,
# while `bbin migrate` (without `auto`) matches the
# SEPARATE entry at cli.clj:40 with `:cmds
# ["migrate"]`.  babashka.cli's `dispatch` performs
# LONGEST-PREFIX matching: when the argv starts
# with `migrate auto`, the two-element entry wins
# over the one-element entry.  Distinct from R269
# Crystal OptionParser (no subcommands), R298 Pony
# (single-level subcommand only), R296 Julia
# Comonicon (`@cast` macro generates `subcmd
# subsubcmd` from nested namespaces).  Closest
# analog: cobra's `Command.AddCommand(...)` tree.
# babashka.cli's data-vector approach is FLATTER:
# nested subcommands live as longer `:cmds` vectors
# in the SAME flat list, rather than as a tree of
# Command objects.  Corpus's **first documented
# flat-list-with-longest-prefix-match nested
# subcommand pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: bbin uses **qualified
# keyword option names** like `--git/sha`, `--mvn/
# version`, `--local/root`, `--http/url` at
# README.md "Supported Options" — Clojure's
# QUALIFIED KEYWORDS (`:git/sha` is a keyword with
# namespace `git` and name `sha`) round-trip
# DIRECTLY into the CLI: `--git/sha VALUE` parses
# to `{:git/sha "VALUE"}` in the opts map.  The
# SLASH in the flag is the Clojure-keyword
# namespace separator.  Distinct from EVERY OTHER
# CLI LIBRARY in the corpus — no other language's
# CLI library accepts SLASHES in long-flag names.
# Documents the **qualified-keyword-as-flag pattern**
# — Clojure-unique.  Trade-off: SLASHES in flag
# names confuse shells that interpret them as path
# separators in path-expansion contexts, but
# babashka.cli's parser reads `--git/sha` as a
# single token before the shell would care.
# Corpus's **first documented slash-in-long-flag-
# name CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: bbin uses **`:args->opts
# [:script/lib]` positional-to-option BINDING** at
# cli.clj:31 — `:args->opts [:script/lib]` declares
# that the FIRST POSITIONAL argv (after the
# subcommand) is bound to the option keyword
# `:script/lib` in the parsed opts map.  So `bbin
# install io.github.babashka/neil` parses to
# `{:script/lib "io.github.babashka/neil"}`.
# Distinct from R287 Nim parseopt (positional
# accumulates in a separate seq), R298 Pony
# (positional declared in `positional` block of
# command_spec), R296 Julia Comonicon
# (`function fn(positional, ...)` arg-list), and
# R301 Nim cligen (`colNums: seq[int]` at end of
# proc-param list).  babashka.cli is UNIQUE:
# positionals are explicitly NAMED via
# `:args->opts` so they live in the SAME opts map
# as the `--flag` options.  No `args` field
# separate from `opts`.  Documents the
# **positional-as-named-option pattern** — corpus's
# **first documented unified-positionals-and-flags
# map**.
#
# Critical extraction note: bbin uses **`*file*`
# main-guard for dual-library-and-binary** at
# cli.clj:88-90 — `(when (= *file* (System/
# getProperty "babashka.file")) (util/check-min-bb-
# version) (apply -main *command-line-args*))`.
# Clojure's `*file*` is the CURRENTLY-LOADED FILE
# path (dynamic var); Babashka's `babashka.file`
# system-property is the FILE PASSED ON THE BB
# COMMAND LINE.  When they're equal, the namespace
# is being run AS THE MAIN ENTRY POINT (not just
# loaded as a library).  Babashka equivalent of
# Python's `if __name__ == "__main__":` and R301
# Nim's `when isMainModule:`.  Distinct from R301
# Nim cligen (`when isMainModule:` is COMPILE-TIME),
# R296 Julia Comonicon (`@main` macro at file
# bottom), and R295 CL clingon (`main()` defun
# called from REPL or `sbcl --script`).  Babashka
# Clojure uses a RUNTIME EQUALITY CHECK because
# `bb` interprets scripts at script-load time, not
# at compile time.  Corpus's **first documented
# Babashka `*file*` guard pattern**.
#
# Hunt-skip notes: skipped `_bb` (Babashka itself,
# already in corpus + blacklisted), `_neil`
# (Babashka tool, already in corpus + blacklisted),
# `_clojure-lsp` (already in corpus), `_cljfmt`
# (already in corpus), `_clj-kondo` (already in
# corpus + blacklisted), `_joker` / `_planck` /
# `_lumo` / `_nbb` / `_shadow-cljs` / `_fennel` /
# `_janet` / `_hy` (all already in corpus).
# Probed `polylith` (Clojure modular workspace, 601
# stars, uses `clojure.tools.cli` — different
# library; deferred for separate round), `kaocha`
# (test runner, uses `clojure.tools.cli`), `eastwood`
# (linter, complex CLI), `clj-new` (deps-style
# tool, no standalone CLI), `deps-new` (same), `cli-
# matic` (the LIBRARY itself, not a CLI tool).
# Chose bbin: AUTHORED BY BABASHKA ORG (rads), 9
# subcommands with rich `:cmds`/`:fn`/`:args->opts`/
# `:aliases` surface, 10 install options including
# Clojure-unique slash-keyword flags `--git/sha` /
# `--mvn/version` / `--local/root`, real Homebrew
# package `babashka/brew/bbin`, stable 0.2.x
# version, used by the broader Babashka script
# ecosystem.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

# bbin subcommand list decoded source-direct from
# cli.clj:24-58 + util.clj help-commands +
# README.md "CLI" section.  Order: README order
# (install, uninstall, ls, bin, version, help) +
# undocumented-but-in-cli.clj (commands, migrate,
# migrate-auto, upgrade).
local -a bbin_subcommands=(
  'install:Install a script'
  'upgrade:Upgrade a script'
  'uninstall:Remove a script'
  'ls:List installed scripts'
  'bin:Display bbin bin folder'
  'version:Display bbin version'
  'help:Display bbin help'
  'migrate:Migrate from bbin v0.1.x'
  'commands:Print subcommand names (one-line)'
)

_arguments -C \
  '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[display bbin help]' \
  '(- *)--version[display bbin version]' \
  '1: :->subcommand' \
  '*:: :->args' && ret=0

case $state in
  subcommand)
    _describe -t commands 'bbin subcommand' bbin_subcommands && ret=0
    ;;
  args)
    case $words[1] in
      install)
        # 10 options decoded source-direct from
        # README.md "install [script]" Supported
        # Options + cli.clj:30-34 aliases
        # `{:T :tool}`.  Slashes in long-flag
        # names are Clojure qualified-keyword
        # round-trip (`--git/sha` → `{:git/sha}`).
        _arguments -s -S \
          '--as=[name of the script to save in the bbin bin path]:name:' \
          '--git/sha=[SHA for a Git repo]:sha:' \
          '--git/tag=[tag for a Git repo]:tag:' \
          '--git/url=[URL for a Git repo]:url:_urls' \
          '--latest-sha[find the latest SHA from the Git repo]' \
          '--local/root=[path of a local directory containing a deps.edn file]:dir:_files -/' \
          '--main-opts=[EDN-format options passed to bb when the script runs]:edn:' \
          '--mvn/version=[version of a Maven dependency]:version:' \
          '--ns-default=[namespace to use to find functions (tool mode only)]:ns:' \
          '(-T --tool)'{-T,--tool}'[install using tool mode (clj -T style entry point)]' \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[display install help]' \
          '1:script lib or url or path:' && ret=0
        ;;
      uninstall)
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[display uninstall help]' \
          '1:installed script name:' && ret=0
        ;;
      upgrade)
        # Same install-style options surface (per
        # scripts.clj load-script + new-script
        # flow at scripts.clj — upgrade reuses
        # install's coord parsing).
        _arguments -s -S \
          '--as=[name of the script to save]:name:' \
          '--git/sha=[SHA for a Git repo]:sha:' \
          '--git/tag=[tag for a Git repo]:tag:' \
          '--git/url=[URL for a Git repo]:url:_urls' \
          '--latest-sha[find the latest SHA from the Git repo]' \
          '--local/root=[path of a local directory containing a deps.edn file]:dir:_files -/' \
          '--main-opts=[EDN-format options passed to bb when the script runs]:edn:' \
          '--mvn/version=[version of a Maven dependency]:version:' \
          '--ns-default=[namespace to use to find functions]:ns:' \
          '(-T --tool)'{-T,--tool}'[upgrade using tool mode]' \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[display upgrade help]' \
          '1:installed script name:' && ret=0
        ;;
      migrate)
        # `migrate auto` is a nested subcommand;
        # plain `migrate` runs an interactive
        # migration.
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[display migrate help]' \
          '1: :(auto)' && ret=0
        ;;
      ls|bin|version|help|commands)
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[display help]' && ret=0
        ;;
    esac
    ;;
esac

return ret
